The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A 16-year-old schoolboy died after being trapped between a tram and a speeding bus on his way back home. The accident occurred at 1.30 pm at the Surya Sen Street-College Street crossing. Rezwan Akhtar, a student of Calcutta Muslim Orphanage High School, was hanging out of the crowded bus when it almost grazed past the tram in an attempt to overtake it. Hit by the tram, Rezwan fell off. Local residents rushed him to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital, where he died.

 Work at Garden Reach Shipbuilders and Engineers was disrupted for over three hours on Monday morning following a clash between Intuc and Citu supporters over distribution of work at the Fitting Out Jetty. Police said Citu had organised a gate-meeting around 8.30 am, demanding that 75 per cent of the work at the jetty be given to its supporters. 

 he present practice is to divide the work equally between supporters of the rival trade unions. When Intuc supporters opposed the Citu demand and tried to enter the jetty, a scuffle broke out between the two groups. Brickbats and bombs were hurled. Two persons have been arrested.

 A 24-year-old housewife suffered 90 per cent burns after she set herself on fire on Monday. She was taken to National Medical College and Hospital, where her condition was stated to be critical. The woman?s husband, Mohammad Rajesh, has been arrested. The couple lives in Avinash Nandy Lane, in Tangra. 

 Mayor Subrata Mukherjee announced on Monday that dependants of nine civic sweepers, who died after consuming illicit liquor in Tangra a few weeks ago, will be given jobs in the Calcutta Municipal Corporation. Following the mayor?s decision, municipal commissioner Debashis Som signed the order for their employment on Monday evening.

 The body recovered on Sunday in Amdanga, on the northern fringes of the city, has been identified as that of a Howrah businessman, who was abducted on Saturday. Police said Bapan Mondal (23), a resident of Daspara, Belur, was murdered inside a vehicle. The assailants later dumped the body beside a road in Amdanga. One man has been arrested.

 The winter session of the legislative assembly begins on December 16. State parliamentary affairs minister Prabodh Sinha said on Monday that around 10 bills will be introduced during the session, which is expected to last a week.

 The vigilance wing of Bureau of Indian Standards (BIS) will conduct raids across the city to nail manufacturers using fake ISI mark on their products. A BIS spokesperson said similar raids are also being carried out elsewhere in the country.

 Dhruba Mondal (17) was lynched by a group of residents of Khudiram Pally, in Duttapukur (North 24-Parganas), on Monday morning. The residents alleged that Dhruba had come to the locality to extort money from traders. They also heaped abuse on his father, Moloy, allegedly a criminal now behind bars. Dhruba was taken to the Barasat district hospital, where he died.

 Members of the Bidhannagar Town Congress rallied in front of the office of the sub-divisional police officer on Monday to protest ?harassment? of innocent people during the recent drives against criminal activities in the township. Police said the demonstration continued for more than an hour from noon.

 Local residents ransacked a shop in Barasat and beat up its owner on Monday morning, after an 18-year-old girl alleged that he had molested her. The girl?s mother has lodged a police complaint.

